'''Murray S. Kessler''' is an [[United States|American]] businessman. He has worked in the food and tobaccco industries. He currently serves as the President, Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer of the [[Lorillard Tobacco Company]] ({{nyse|LO}}).

==Biography==
===Early life===
He received a Bachelor of Science in Business Administration from [[Villanova University]] and an Master's in Business Administration in Marketing and Finance from the [[New York University Stern School of Business]].<ref name="management">[http://www.lorillard.com/about-us/management/murray-s-kessler/ Lorillard Management]</ref><ref name="businessweek">[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=190884&ticker=UST Bloomberg BusinessWeek]</ref><ref name="forbes">[http://www.forbes.com/lists/2012/12/ceo-compensation-12_Murray-S-Kessler_4ECD.html Forbes]</ref>

===Career===
He started his career at the [[Campbell Soup Company]] ({{NYSE|CPB}}) and [[Clorox]] ({{nyse|CLX}}).<ref name="management"/><ref name="wsj">[http://topics.wsj.com/person/K/murray-kessler/786 The Wall Street Journal]</ref> He served as Vice President of Sales and Marketing of [[Pace Foods]], a division of Campbell Soup, from September 1995 to October 1997.<ref name="businessweek"/> He served as General Manager of the [[Swanson]] Division of Campbell Soup from October 1997 to March 1998.<ref name="businessweek"/> He served as Vice President of [[Pinnacle Foods]] ({{New York Stock Exchange|PF}}) from March 1998 to December 1999.<ref name="businessweek"/>

He served as President of the [[U.S. Smokeless Tobacco Company]] (UST) from April 2000 to October 2005, and as its President and Chief Operating Officer from November 2005 to December 2006.<ref name="management"/><ref name="businessweek"/> He served as its President and Chief Executive Officer from January 2007 to 2009.<ref name="management"/><ref name="businessweek"/> Additionally, from 2008 to 2009, he served as its Chairman.<ref name="management"/><ref name="businessweek"/>

From 2009 to 2010, he served as Vice Chair of [[Altria]] ({{NYSE|MO}}).<ref name="management"/><ref name="businessweek"/><ref name="wsj"/>

In September 2010, he joined the Lorillard Tobacco Company as President and Chief Executive Officer, as well as member of its Board of Directors, replacing [[Martin L. Orlowsky]].<ref name="management"/><ref name="businessweek"/><ref name="forbes"/> Additionally, he has served as its Chairman since January 1, 2011.<ref name="management"/> In 2012, he earned US$3.2 million.<ref name="forbes"/>

In 2012, he donated money to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] like [[Mitt Romney]] for the presidency, [[Chris Shays]] for Congressman, [[Howard Coble]] for Senator, [[George Allen (U.S. politician)|George Allen]] for Senator, [[Mitch McConnell]] for Senator, as well as [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] like [[Kay Hagan]] for Senator, and [[Susan Bysiewicz]] for Secretary of State of Connecticut.<ref>[http://www.campaignmoney.com/political/contributions/murray-kessler.asp?cycle=12 Campaign Money 2012]</ref>

